The Realtek RTL8126 5GbE controller advertises a PCI VPD capability, but
on Orion O6 systems using the dedicated r8126 driver, userspace attempts
to read the sysfs VPD attribute can fail with:

  pcilib: sysfs_read_vpd: read failed: No such device

This is visible in `lspci -vvnn` for the RTL8126 endpoints.  VPD is
optional PCI metadata; failing to read it does not affect normal device
operation, but exposing a VPD sysfs file that cannot be read makes routine
diagnostic output look like a live PCI failure.

The PCI core already has a VPD blacklist for devices that advertise VPD but
do not provide a standard, safely-readable VPD area.  Add the RTL8126 to
that list so the core does not expose broken VPD access for these devices.

This is intentionally narrow: it only disables optional VPD access for
Realtek device ID 0x8126 and does not change PCI enumeration, power
management, ASPM, MSI/MSI-X, or the network driver binding.

---
 drivers/pci/vpd.c | 1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

diff --git a/drivers/pci/vpd.c b/drivers/pci/vpd.c
--- a/drivers/pci/vpd.c
+++ b/drivers/pci/vpd.c
@@ -590,6 +590,7 @@ DECLARE_PCI_FIXUP_HEADER(PCI_VENDOR_ID_LSI_LOGIC, 0x002f, quirk_blacklist_vpd);
 DECLARE_PCI_FIXUP_HEADER(PCI_VENDOR_ID_LSI_LOGIC, 0x005d, quirk_blacklist_vpd);
 DECLARE_PCI_FIXUP_HEADER(PCI_VENDOR_ID_LSI_LOGIC, 0x005f, quirk_blacklist_vpd);
 DECLARE_PCI_FIXUP_HEADER(PCI_VENDOR_ID_ATTANSIC, PCI_ANY_ID, quirk_blacklist_vpd);
+DECLARE_PCI_FIXUP_HEADER(PCI_VENDOR_ID_REALTEK, 0x8126, quirk_blacklist_vpd);
 /*
  * The Amazon Annapurna Labs 0x0031 device id is reused for other non Root Port
  * device types, so the quirk is registered for the PCI_CLASS_BRIDGE_PCI class.
-- 
